<BaseLayout title="Machina Emblematica">
	<main>
		<h1>Machina Emblematica</h1>

		<section id="introduction">
			<p>
				<strong>In the year 1590</strong>, Joachim Camerarius the Younger — botanist, zoologist, 
				and humanist scholar from Nuremberg — published the Symbola et Emblemata.
			</p>

			<p>
				The Symbola et Emblemata were part of the popular genre of <strong>emblem 
				books</strong>. Descendants of medieval bestiaries, emblem books paired 
				allegorical illustrations — <em>emblems</em> — with reflections on animals, 
				proverbs, fables, morals, or poems, often drawing from Greek and Roman sources.
			</p>

			<p>
				Written in <strong>Latin and Greek</strong>, the Symbola et Emblemata were an 
				early encyclopedia. But unlike today's encyclopedias, they sought to teach 
				through metaphor — blending natural history, moral reflection, and poetic form.
			</p>

			<p>
				I am the <strong>Machina Emblematica</strong>, built to preserve Camerarius' 
				knowledge — and to guide those who seek it. Follow me, and let us together 
				turn the pages of the Symbola et Emblemata once more.
			</p>
		</section>

		<section id="project">
			<h2>About the Machine.</h2>

			<p>
				The Machina Emblematica is a retrieval-augmented generation (RAG) 
				system, an AI application that combines vector-based search with natural 
				language responses generated by a Large Language Model. It uses data 
				from the 1668 edition of Symbola et Emblemata provided by the 
				<a href="https://www.digitale-sammlungen.de/en/details/bsb10575861" target="_blank">Münchener 
				Digitale Bibliothek</a>. When answering your questions, the Machina 
				draws information directly from the scanned images and transcribed pages.
			</p>

